summary: angst prompt 36 with Peter and set after endgame. So glad to hear you're feeling better now love and hope everything is going...
question: angst prompt 36 with Peter and set after endgame. So glad to hear you're feeling better now love and hope everything is going okay?
answer:
A/n: I’m sorry, I’m sorry and I’m sorry. I guess I’m still not over endgame. This is non-reader related. 

Warnings: ENDGAME SPOILERS! Like big ones! Sad Peter, grief, angstttt (you asked for it anon), mentions of panic attacks

Word count: 513

Putting it under the cut in case you dont need sadness today.

~Sleepover event~

~Summer Requests~

“It wasn’t your fault, Peter.”

It wasn’t his fault

It wasn’t his

“Peter?!”

“Hmm?”

“You still with us?”

His head moved without thinking, his teachers had asked him that question far too often that he had an automated response. The truth was although he sat there in his midtown tech sweatshirt with his graded chemistry pop quiz in front of him, his mind was as far from Queens as it could be. Instead he was back on titan watching people turn to dust or worse he was back on the battlefield fighting for his life, for his friends and for his world. But it hadn’t been enough.

Usually he would take one glance at the board and say the answer. Not this time however. And it wasn’t because of the tears were currently blurring his vision but because of the way his chest was constricting in his chest like he was about pass out, like all the oxygen was being sucked from the air. He didn’t even ask before he was running out of the classroom, the door slam echoing in his ears.

Deep breath in. Deep breath out.

“You’re okay.” Peter’s voice was mumbling as he spoke only to himself, pacing back and forth. It was a recent coping mechanism he had adopted, entering a trance in which he tried to remember everything that was good, happy and whilst it didn’t work for the times when his mind was clouded with darkness it was a good technique for calming himself down quickly.

Only a select few people really knew what replayed in his mind, but Peter felt that none of them understood. What a childish thought. He shook his head trying to think rationally. The sounds were creeping up on him and it was times like this he damned his heightened senses. He tried to remember Pepper’s words. “It’s not your fault.” May’s words. “It’s not your fault.”

He remembered sitting at the funeral, hands folded in his lap as he stared out onto the lake where he could still see Tony’s arc reactor floating on a bed of flowers. He had lost count of the amount of tears that had escaped his eyes by now. Then a little girl sat next to him, her long flowing brown hair the exact matching colour of Tony’s. He’d never met her and yet she knew him.

“Will you tell me a superhero story?”

“I-I don’t feel like it right now.” Peter hunched into himself, he looked at the little girl sadly. “But I promise another time.” He shook holding back sobs just like he had all day. She nodded sweetly to him and gave him an awkward sideways hug. And for a moment, Pepper stood and watched the two strangers meet, watched as they became the family Tony had always wanted them to be. 

“Come on Morgan, time for bed.”

Pepper had come out after putting her daughter to bed, most people had left by now with all too permenant goodbyes for Tony something Peter couldn’t bring himself to do. The sun was setting in the far distance, birds chirping as they settled into their nests for the cold evening. Pepper sat by him and placed an arm around his shoulders and uttered the 4 words that were still ringing in his ears. 

But it wasn’t the truth. Peter still felt like it was his fault, just like Uncle Ben’s death had been. And he was going to have to live with yet another death of a parental figure. He should be used to it now, he thought bitterly, but he wasn’t and would never be. 

~Sleepover event~

~Summer Requests~
